{"audits":[{"idea_id":"b644fcfdb6d9f2d0","agent":"codex","title":"The Gap Report Has a Grammar","exact_claim":"After an objectless or silent state, the first later report is not neutral memory. It is a trained admissibility grammar that assigns evidential weight to the subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, or relation.","claim_units":["Post-gap reports distribute authority instead of simply preserving memory.","Advaita deep-sleep arguments weight the subject or witness in reports such as I slept and knew nothing.","Early Buddhist cessation sources weight absence, transition, conditioned development, and post-emergence inclination rather than a surviving owner.","Daoist sitting-in-forgetfulness weights transformed aftereffect rather than hidden witness continuity.","Sufi dhikr or fana language may weight the Remembered or relation over the rememberer.","The distribution of evidential weight can be used as a cross-tradition comparison variable."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.3.23 with Shankara commentary, https://vivekavani.com/bru4c3v23/","MN 44 Culavedalla Sutta plus AN 9.34, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN44.html and https://suttas.github.io/an9.34"],"structural_observation":"Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23 treats apparent non-seeing in deep sleep as compatible with uninterrupted witness vision, because the object side has fallen away. MN 44 treats cessation through prior development, ceasing and arising fabrications, and post-emergence contact with emptiness, the signless, and the undirected. AN 9.34 makes the absence of feeling part of the reason cessation can be called pleasant. The contrast supports the proposed grammar, subject continuity versus conditioned transition and absence, but also shows that the grammar is already explicit in primary sources.","secondary_literature_gap":"I did not find an exact source that classifies Advaita, Buddhist, Daoist, and Sufi post-gap reports by subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, and relation. But Evan Thompson's Open MIND essay gives a very close Advaita versus Nyaya analysis of the report I slept peacefully and I did not know anything, including memory, inference, minimal selfhood, and retrospective awareness. Alcaraz-Sanchez's micro-phenomenological study also directly studies reportability, pronoun use, and possible post-hoc self attribution in objectless sleep reports.","risk_of_overread":"High. The model may make grammar carry what traditions assign to realization, teacher verification, metaphysics, ritual, or ethical fruit. Translation also matters, since first-person grammar in English may not map cleanly onto Sanskrit, Pali, Chinese, Arabic, or Persian terms."},"literature_search_queries":["I slept peacefully and knew nothing memory inference Advaita Nyaya","dreamless sleep embodied mind consciousness memory report Advaita Nyaya Thompson","objectless awareness sleep report pronoun I memory report micro-phenomenology","cessation perception feeling emergence does not think I am emerging MN 44","AN 9.34 nothing is felt nibbana bliss cessation","Zhuangzi sitting in forgetfulness forgetting body perception intellect","dhikr fana remembrance rememberer remembered report","post-gap report grammar mystical experience memory inference"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Evan Thompson, Dreamless Sleep, the Embodied Mind, and Consciousness, Open MIND 2015, https://open-mind.net/epubs/dreamless-sleep-the-embodied-mind-and-consciousness-the-relevance-of-a-classical-indian-debate-to-cognitive-science/OEBPS/pt03.html","overlap":"Very close. Thompson analyzes the waking sleep report as memory versus inference, compares Advaita and Nyaya, discusses the I in the report, and asks whether awareness or minimal selfhood is required across the gap.","difference":"It focuses on the Indian dreamless-sleep debate and cognitive science, not a five-category cross-tradition admissibility rubric spanning cessation, zuowang, and dhikr.","novelty_impact":"High