spectral analysis, PMC, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10843092/","overlap":"Treats cessation as a discontinuity followed by reported changes in clarity and mental functioning, close to the transition and aftereffect part of the model.","difference":"It studies neural and phenomenological correlates of Buddhist cessation, not comparative spiritual hermeneutics of report clauses.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction for empirical-adjacent testability."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike Thompson on Advaita and Nyaya, or micro-phenomenology on objectless sleep reports, this idea says the evidential clause selected after a gap is a cross-tradition admissibility rule that can be coded across subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, and relation.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Tibetan clear-light sleep and contemporary objectless-awareness sleep reports that claim awareness during the gap, not only after it.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If trained practitioners can give stable, carefully interviewed reports of awareness while the gap is unfolding, then the later report is not merely assigning evidence after an uninspectable silence. The model would need to distinguish in-gap phenomenology from post-gap evidential framing.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence from candidate discovery to extended. The anomaly does not reject the model, but it makes post-gap grammar secondary rather than foundational in some cases."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"Traditions should show stable differences in which clause of a post-gap report they treat as admissible evidence.","expected_observation":"Advaita materials should privilege witness or subject continuity; early Buddhist cessation materials should privilege cessation, transition, and fruit; Daoist zuowang should privilege aftereffect and forgetting; dhikr or fana materials should privilege relation or the Remembered.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"If evidence weights vary mainly by translator, genre, or individual teacher rather than tradition and method, the model loses predictive value.","test_surface":"Blind coding of primary texts, practice manuals, and practitioner interviews using subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, teacher recognition, and behavioral fruit tags."},{"if_model_is_right":"Dual-trained practitioners should shift evidential weighting when switching practice frames.","expected_observation":"The same practitioner speaks differently about sleep, cessation, or objectless meditation under Advaita, Theravada, and Tibetan prompts.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Practitioners preserve the same evidential interpretation across frames, or report that the distinction is imposed by the interviewer.","test_surface":"Structured interviews with dual-trained Advaita, Buddhist, Sufi, Daoist, and micro-phenomenology-trained practitioners."},{"if_model_is_right":"Original-language terms should support the proposed categories, not merely English pronoun artifacts.","expected_observation":"Sanskrit, Pali, Chinese, Arabic, or Persian sources should mark subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, or relation through recurring lexical and grammatical patterns.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"The categories disappear or become unstable when checked against original terms and multiple translations.","test_surface":"Close read of Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23, Yoga Sutra 1.10, MN 44, AN 9.34, Zhuangzi zuowang passages, and primary dhikr or fana texts."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Advaita Vedanta teachers using three-state analysis","Theravada teachers familiar with nirodha samapatti","Tibetan dream yoga or clear-light sleep practitioners","Daoist practitioners familiar with zuowang","Sufi teachers familiar with dhikr, fana, and baqa","Micro-phenomenology researchers of sleep and meditation"],"questions":["When you hear a report after deep sleep, cessation, forgetting, or remembrance, which part of the report counts as evidence?","Is this report-weighting obvious within your training, or does naming it change how the practice is understood?","Would your tradition reject another tradition's report because it weights the wrong clause?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners say the distinction is already standard as pramana, memory versus inference, fruition review, teacher verification, or adab of remembrance, and that the new labels do not change practice.","answers_that_support_contribution":"Practitioners can use the rubric to explain why cross-tradition disputes persist even when phenomenological reports sound similar."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Anesthesia, blackout, trauma, and psychedelic integration reports","structural_translation":"After an interval that cannot be inspected while it occurs, communities decide whether to trust subject continuity, absence of recall, physiological transition, aftereffects, or relational testimony.","prediction":"Clinical and legal settings should show different admissibility grammars for blackout reports, anesthesia emergence, trauma memory, and psychedelic ego dissolution, and these grammars should predict what is treated as evidence of continuity, harm, or transformation.","would_count_against_it":"If these domains use no stable admissibility patterns, or if all rely only on external measurement regardless of later report structure, the proposed structure may be limited to contemplative rhetoric."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.78,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.58,"source_reliability":0.79,"counterargument_quality":0.9},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.71 to about 0.58. The cross-tradition admissibility rubric is useful, but the report grammar of dreamless sleep, memory, inference, witness, and post-hoc self attribution has close prior art.","next_loop_instructions":["Close-read Thompson against Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23, Yoga Sutra 1.10, MN 44, and AN 9.34 before promoting the idea.","Build a coding rubric for post-gap reports with mutually exclusive and mixed tags: subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, teacher recognition, behavioral fruit.","Test clear-light sleep and objectless-awareness reports as the anomaly class, using micro-phenomenological interview methods and serial awakening literature.","Check original languages and multiple translations before treating English first-person phrasing as evidence.","Ask practitioners whether the rubric changes cross-tradition interpretation or only renames familiar evidential disputes."]},{"idea_id":"3c5caa358a09c26a","agent":"claude","title":"Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves","exact_claim":"A path that dissolves, denies, or transcends selfhood still requires a minimum functioning self, agency, memory, reflexivity, and continuity, and each tradition's strategy for managing that requirement predicts its practice architecture.","claim_units":["Self-dissolving practice presupposes capacities for hearing instruction, effort, memory, error recognition, and self-observation.","SN 22.59 dissolves the person while preserving the causal process of liberation.","Chandogya 6.8.7 preserves the deepest Self while dissolving the reality of the student's apparent process.","Causal continuity, ontological identity, temporal collapse, and divine restoration are proposed as management strategies.","The management strategy should predict effort theory, verification, warnings, and post-practice fruit."],"primary_text_close_read":{"primary_pair":["SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html","Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 through 6.16.3, https://shlokam.org/texts/Chandogya-6-8-7 and https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/chandogya-upanishad-english/d/doc239333.html"],"structural_observation":"SN 22.59 requires monks who can listen, answer, inspect each aggregate, and become disenchanted, yet it denies that any aggregate, including consciousness, is fit to be self. Its closing grammar says the monks' minds were released, preserving process without owner. Chandogya repeatedly addresses Shvetaketu as a learner asking for more explanation, yet the repeated teaching identifies him with the Self of all this. This supports the proposed tension, but it is not new by itself. It is close to classical Buddhist debates over personhood and to Advaita pedagogy around recognizing the already present Self.","secondary_literature_gap":"I did not find an exact four-strategy cross-tradition typology that predicts architecture across Buddhism, Advaita, Zen, and Sufism. But the main pressure is heavily precedented in Buddhist personhood debates, Pudgalavada arguments, Collins on selfless persons, Engler on ego strength before no-self, functional-self accounts in Buddhist psychology, and contemporary self-pattern theories of meditation.","risk_of_overread":"High. The model may turn a researcher's philosophical tension into a practitioner's lived problem. It also risks forcing mixed traditions into clean boxes. Theravada, Zen, Advaita, Sufism, Dzogchen, and Christian grace traditions often combine effort, surrender, recognition, teacher relation, and ethical transformation across stages."},"literature_search_queries":["who practices if there is no self Buddhism liberation agency","Pudgalavada karma rebirth liberation person no self","Selfless Persons Theravada personal identity continuity denial of self Collins","you have to be somebody before you can be nobody Engler Buddhism meditation","functional self Buddhist no-self mindfulness trauma preliminary practice","minimal self meditation non-self self-pattern agency ownership","Dogen practice-realization beginner original enlightenment Bendowa","praptasya prapti attainment of the already attained Advaita Shankara"],"near_neighbors":[{"source":"Jack Engler interview, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, Inquiring Mind, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/","overlap":"Very close. Engler says meditation requires ego strength, self-observation, and affect tolerance before no-self can be safely practiced.","difference":"Engler's frame is Buddhist psychology and psychotherapy. He does not build a comparative typology of causal continuity, ontological identity, temporal collapse, and divine restoration across traditions.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The core minimum-self prerequisite is already a well-known practitioner-facing thesis."},{"source":"Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/","overlap":"Very close historical prior art. Pudgalavadins argued that karma, rebirth, liberation, benevolence, and lived personhood strain a strict no-self aggregate account.","difference":"This is an intra-Buddhist metaphysical and doctrinal dispute, not a general model of practice architecture across traditions.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. The pressure between no-self and soteriological functioning is ancient, not newly discovered."},{"source":"Steven Collins, Selfless Persons, summary and citation, https://buddhanature.tsadra.org/index.php/Books/Selfless_Persons","overlap":"Collins directly studies how Theravada constructs personal identity and continuity on the apparently impossible basis of denying self.","difference":"The focus is Theravada discourse and imagery, not cross-tradition engineering constraints.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the Buddhist side. The Lumenary idea extends rather than originates the continuity problem."},{"source":"Tempone-Wiltshire and Dowie, A Mindful Bypassing, Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies, https://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/269","overlap":"Close. The article links anatta, the person, cognitive-science selfhood, functional self, trauma, and preliminary practice before transpersonal or soteriological work.","difference":"Clinical mindfulness and trauma are the focus, not comparative religion typology.","novelty_impact":"High reduction for the functional-self and warning-profile elements."},{"source":"Not-Self Sutra, Barre Center for Buddhist Studies, https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/not-self-sutra/","overlap":"Extremely close for the Buddhist unit. It speaks of functional or enactive self, minimal self, agency without ownership, and discipline through causes and conditions.","difference":"It is a contemporary Buddhist exposition rather than a cross-tradition predictive model.","novelty_impact":"High reduction. Parts of the Lumenary wording risk being a renamed Buddhist functional-self account."},{"source":"Pattern Theory of Selflessness, Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2","overlap":"Close contemporary theory. It distinguishes minimal self, ownership, agency, self-pattern, and how meditation transforms self-processes toward selflessness.","difference":"It is cognitive-scientific and Buddhist-psychological rather than a primary-text comparative architecture model.","novelty_impact":"Moderate to high reduction for the minimal-self and practice-transformation language."},{"source":"Dogen practice-realization sources, for example Soto and Bendowa summaries, https://zenlineage.org/schools/soto and https://buddhismnow.com/2023/10/08/practice-within-realisation-dogen/","overlap":"The temporal-collapse strategy is already central to Dogen's practice-realization, where practice is not merely a means to later awakening.","difference":"It does not compare this strategy against Advaita, Theravada, and Sufi models of self-continuity.","novelty_impact":"Moderate reduction. The Zen strategy is known; the comparative placement may still be useful."}],"unlike_statement":"Unlike Engler, Pudgalavada debates, Collins, or functional-self Buddhist psychology, this idea treats the minimum self as a comparative architecture variable across traditions and claims it predicts effort, verification, warnings, and fruit.","anomaly_probe":{"anomaly_candidate":"Other-power and direct-introduction traditions, such as Jodo Shinshu entrusting and Dzogchen pointing-out, appear to minimize self-powered agency while still functioning as paths.","why_it_breaks_or_strains_model":"If a tradition can produce stable transformation through vow, grace, devotion, direct introduction, or teacher-field participation with very little reflexive self-management, then the minimum self may not be an architectural driver. The model would need a scale of required self-capacities rather than a universal requirement.","confidence_effect":"Lowers confidence in the universal form of the claim. It supports a revised model where paths require some functional receiving capacity, but the amount and role vary sharply."},"falsifiable_predictions":[{"if_model_is_right":"The stronger a path's final self-dissolution claim, the more explicit its safeguards should be against premature or distorted self-loss.","expected_observation":"Manuals and teachers should warn against nihilism, dissociation, spiritual bypassing, false attainment, antinomianism, or ego-inflation in ways that match the path's self-management strategy.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Warnings show no relationship to self-teaching and track only institution, teacher personality, or general ethics.","test_surface":"Coded comparison of Theravada, Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, Sufi, Christian apophatic, and Pure Land training materials."},{"if_model_is_right":"Long, effortful paths should develop more elaborate continuity mechanisms than sudden or other-power paths.","expected_observation":"Theravada stages, Sufi stations, and Advaita preparation should specify capacities, sequence, and error correction; sudden methods should shift burden to teacher recognition, pointing-out, vows, or post-recognition integration.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Practice length and self-continuity machinery are unrelated, or sudden paths have equally elaborate minimum-self architecture before recognition.","test_surface":"Comparative coding of practice sequences, teacher-student protocols, and attainment verification."},{"if_model_is_right":"Dual-trained practitioners should report different kinds of permitted selfhood when switching methods.","expected_observation":"Vipassana permits causal observation without ownership; Advaita permits witness or Self recognition; Soto Zen discourages gaining selfhood; Sufi practice permits surrendering agency into relation with God.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"Practitioners report no stable shift, or the shifts are better explained by temperament and teacher style.","test_surface":"Structured interviews with practitioners trained in two or more lineages."},{"if_model_is_right":"The point where a method consumes its prerequisite should be specially marked as difficult, risky, or decisive.","expected_observation":"Texts and practitioners should mark investigation of the investigator, hearing tat tvam asi, fana, kensho, pointing-out, or surrender as a crisis or verification point.","would_weaken_or_falsify":"These moments are not specially marked, or transformation is described as ordinary continuity without any self-prerequisite tension.","test_surface":"Primary-text close reading plus practitioner interviews and retreat-report coding."}],"practitioner_test":{"relevant_practitioners":["Theravada monastics and insight teachers","Advaita Vedanta teachers","Soto and Rinzai Zen teachers","Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers","Sufi teachers familiar with fana and baqa","Pure Land teachers familiar with other-power","Buddhist psychotherapists and trauma-informed mindfulness teachers"],"questions":["Does your path require a functional self-capacity that its final teaching later dissolves, denies, or reframes?","Is this already obvious as two truths, healthy ego before no-self, practice-realization, surrender, or grace?","Would this rubric change how you screen students, sequence practices, verify insight, or warn against errors?"],"answers_that_reduce_originality":"Practitioners identify the idea as already standard: conventional person versus ultimate no-self, somebody before nobody, sadhana before recognition, practice-realization, fana and baqa, or other-power entrusting.","answers_that_support_contribution":"Practitioners find that the rubric predicts real training differences and clarifies why premature self-dissolution, clinging to witness, bypassing, or false surrender fail differently across paths."},"cross_domain_prediction":{"domain":"Psychotherapy and transformative education","structural_translation":"Any method that aims to dissolve or radically transform the learner's starting identity must preserve enough agency, memory, trust, and reflexivity for the method to work.","prediction":"Therapies or pedagogies that deconstruct identity, such as trauma therapy, exposure therapy, psychedelic therapy, contemplative psychotherapy, or critical pedagogy, should have stronger screening, scaffolding, integration, and teacher-client safeguards than methods that merely add skills.","would_count_against_it":"If deconstructive methods require no more scaffolding than ordinary skills training, or if safeguards do not track the degree of identity transformation, the structural claim is weakened."},"originality_status":"extended","confidence":0.82,"recommended_scores":{"novelty":0.52,"source_reliability":0.82,"counterargument_quality":0.91},"novelty_adjustment":"Reduce novelty from 0.74 to about 0.52. The cross-tradition architecture claim is a meaningful extension, but the minimum-self prerequisite, functional self, no-self continuity problem, and healthy ego before no-self are strong prior art.","next_loop_instructions":["Recast the model as a graded variable: required receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration.","Separate Buddhist two-truths and personhood prior art from the cross-tradition contribution before publication.","Add Pure Land other-power, Christian grace, and Dzogchen pointing-out as anomaly cases, not footnotes.","Ask practitioners whether the model predicts actual screening, sequencing, warning, and verification practices.","Search further in Engler, Wilber, Brown, Collins, Harvey, Duerlinger, Siderits, Albahari, Buddhist trauma literature, practice-realization scholarship, fana and baqa sources, and Advaita praptasya prapti discussions."]}]}
